+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01VbPouPLhSfreqs4exojcjY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"What the merge algorithm says that I couldn't: **The common ancestor isn't a single document — it's the entire state of all documents at the fork point.** When branch B forked from branch A, the ancestor state is a snapshot of every document as it existed at that moment. Documents created after the fork exist only on one side and should merge cleanly. Documents deleted after the fork on one side but modified on the other — that's a conflict at the document level, not the field level. The merge walks documents first, then fields. Two levels of structural recursion.\n\nAlso: **the fork point must be captured eagerly, not computed lazily.** At branch creation time, deep-clone the entire branch state. This is the base for future merges. Simple and correct."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":138,"cache_read_input_tokens":20884,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":138},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5310e806-0cab-416e-a97f-656da9a8c731","uuid":"ab3b8339-61b5-46a2-9639-c7bd292bd8a4"}
